<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-699-787  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 699 787.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Networking Management  Dec 1990 v8 n12 p16(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Noted for packages, UPS also &quot;delivers&quot; in advanced networkingtechnology. (United Parcel Service)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Weber, James A.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Steven Heit, information services planning manager for UnitedParcel SErvice (UPS) says his company's technological growth isdriven by several factors: competitive need to automate operationsto provide the best services at the lowest rates and increasingdemand to provide comprehensive,information-based services.andP;  In1985 the company began a $1.4-billion 5-year plan for upgradingtechnology.andP;  UPS replaced 93 IBM 8100 minicomputers with over 300local area networks (LANs) using IBM Token-Ring hardware andNovell NetWare operating system software and 4500 PC workstationsat 200 sites worldwide.andP;  More efficient transmission capabilitiesand lower telecommunications costs are made possible by the bettergateways in PCs.andP;  The gateways link LANs to mainframe computersthrough UPSnet, a network that transmits voice, data, facsimile,video, and still images between the US offices.andP;  UPSnet operateswith 39 X.25 switches linked to 7 notes or T1 multiplexers viahigh-capacity communication links.andP;  The concept of UPSnet is 'anyto any', any protocol bit transport level, any data to any site,in any format.andP;  UPS uses modularity as its application developmentphilosophy.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   United Parcel Service of America Inc. (Automation).andO;Topic:     Case StudyNetworksCompaniesLocal Area NetworksTelecommunicationsParcel Delivery.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>